36. non cuivis, etc.: i.e. the nobleness of the career is shown by the fact that everybody cannot suc- ceed in it. This thought is put in the form of the Greek proverb, οὐ παντὸς ἀνδρὸς ἐς Κόρινθον ἔσθ’ ὖ πλοῦς. The origin of the proverb is unknown, but its form suggests a quotation from some play. The ex- planation of Gellius (I. 8) referring it to the famous courtesan Lais sounds like a later invention. But at any rate the proverb carne to be used of anything which everybody could not attain.

37. sedit qui timuit, etc.: this verse, which has the style of the sen- tentious single-line colloquies of the Greek tragedy, is either purposely imitated by Horace from that style, or it may possibly be actually quoted from the same play as the proverb. Although the connection is difficult, and has been much. debated, it seems best to take the statement as {²0 ‘23155312335 ’ 5,ῗὲῗέἛηῖῗὲἳῖἓέ
